Alibaba invests $200m in Snapchat
Chinese internet giant Alibaba has invested approximately $200m (£133m) in a stake in messaging application Snapchat, the BBC understands.That values the four-year old firm at nearly $15bn (£10bn)makes it one of the world's most valuable start-ups.Snapchat allows users to send text and picture messages which disappear in 10 seconds.Snapchat says its users send 700 million snaps daily, recently started generating revenue from advertising.The $15bn valuation puts the business in a league with taxi service Uber and Xiaomi, the Chinese smartphone maker.Alibaba has invested in a range of start-ups in China, but its portfolio in the US is relatively small.The company has stakes in video call app TangoMe and Lyft, a competitor to Uber.